# Deploy park-landing to Production

## Branches

| Branch | Purpose | Railway env |
|---|---|---|
| `development` | Larger refactors / WIP that isn't ready for `main` | — |
| `main` | Stable copy ready to ship | (not auto-deployed) |
| `production` | Live site | production (auto-deploy) |

`production` is the single branch that drives Railway deploys. Pushing
to `main` does NOT deploy. This convention is shared across all
Railway-deployed repos in the BuildingPark stack (backend, crm, portal,
landing).

## Deployment Steps

### 1. Ensure main is clean and pushed

```bash
cd /Users/omer/Documents/omer/park-landing
git checkout main
git status          # must be clean
git push origin main
```

### 2. Merge main → production

```bash
git checkout production
git pull origin production          # sync with remote first
git merge main --no-edit            # fast-forward when possible
```

### 3. Push production to trigger Railway deploy

```bash
git push origin production
```

### 4. Switch back to main

```bash
git checkout main
```

### 5. Verify deployment

- Railway auto-deploys on push to `production`
- The landing is a static site served by nginx (see `Dockerfile` and
  `nginx.conf`). Verify:
  - `/` (home) loads
  - `/delete-account` loads (Google Play compliance)
  - any contact / lead-form CTA still works
- If you added new HTML files, double-check `nginx.conf` serves them

## Quick one-liner (when everything is already pushed to main)

```bash
git checkout production && git pull origin production && git merge main --no-edit && git push origin production && git checkout main
```

## Rollback

If production breaks after deploy:

```bash
git checkout production
git revert HEAD --no-edit       # revert the merge commit
git push origin production
git checkout main
```

## Rules

- NEVER force-push to `production`
- NEVER commit directly to `production` — always merge from `main`
- The landing is the public face of the brand. Sanity-check on a
  desktop AND a mobile viewport before merging to `main` (it ships
  to `production` immediately after via the flow above)
- The `/delete-account` page is required by Google Play. If you
  ever rename or remove it, update the listing first
